How it works
1. Server boots (server.js)
Starts a Next.js HTTP server on port 3000
Starts a WebSocket server on port 3001
Seeds 2800px of fake price history by running the simulation
Calls consume_vrf on-chain → gets back randomness, computes which row the pointer should land on for each upcoming column (stored in vrfPath map)
2. Pointer tick (every 33ms)
serverCurrentX advances by 1px
stepSim() moves simY (0–1, where 1=top, 0=bottom)
steerTowardRow() nudges velocity toward the VRF-predetermined row for the current column — so the pointer naturally drifts toward the winning row
When the pointer crosses into a new column, it records columnActualRow[prevColX] = actual row pointer was on
Broadcasts { type: 'pointer', y, multiplier, currentX } to all WS clients
3. User clicks a box (browser)
StockGrid detects the click, fires a custom event sprmfun:select with { colX, row }
GameHUD catches it, shows the bet modal
4. Bet placement
User confirms → handlePlaceBet runs:
Encodes box_x as 8-byte little-endian for PDA seed
Derives betPda = [b"bet", userPubkey, box_x_le8, box_row]
Calls place_bet(box_x, box_row, amount) on-chain
Transfers tokens from user ATA → escrow ATA
Signs via Phantom, sends to localnet via sendRawTransaction
After confirmed, POSTs to /register-bet (HTTP on port 3000)
Server adds bet to pendingBets map: betPda → { betPda, user, box_x, box_row, userAta }
5. Auto-resolve
Every pointer tick, server checks: for each pending bet, if serverCurrentX >= bet.box_x + COLUMN_WIDTH → resolveBet()
resolveBet() looks up columnActualRow[colX] — the row the pointer was actually on when it left that column
Calls resolve_bet(winning_row) on-chain (authority signs)
On-chain: if bet.box_row == winning_row → computes gross = amount × multiplier, takes 2% fee, transfers net to user ATA
Broadcasts { type: 'bet_resolved', won, box_x, box_row, winning_row } to all WS clients
Browser shows WIN/LOSE flash, balance updates
6. VRF refresh (every ~8 columns)
Server calls consume_vrf(newRandomness, newSalt) on-chain
Pre-computes winning rows for next 8 columns using sha256(vrf || salt || colX)[0] % 10
Broadcasts path_revealed to clients so they can highlight the VRF-winning row (gold tint)






