Got it — every row the pointer passes through in a column wins. So if the pointer enters at row 2 and exits at row 7, rows 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 all win.

This means instead of a single winning_row, we need a set of winning rows per column. The on-chain resolve_bet just needs to check if bet.box_row is in that set.

The simplest representation: a bitmask (10 rows → fits in a u16). Let me update the contract and server:

